      <hedline>
        <hl1>On Campus, Diversity or Unity?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof James A McLennan letter says college faculties share responsibility for promoting diversity on campus</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Campus Divided, and Divided Again,'' by Arthur Levine (Op-Ed, June 11):</p>
        <p>Mr. Levine may be correct that students are ''the engine for action on diversity at most colleges,'' but the faculty also shares responsibility.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Campus Divided, and Divided Again,'' by Arthur Levine (Op-Ed, June 11):</p>
        <p>Mr. Levine may be correct that students are ''the engine for action on diversity at most colleges,'' but the faculty also shares responsibility.</p>
        <p>The curriculum has been fragmented to give opportunity for the teaching of specialized courses with content adapted to the professor's particular interests, and the explosion of course listings in the catalog predates the current diversity movement.</p>
        <p>Adherence to the old notion of a liberal education, with a small number of courses covering fundamental subjects and with much commonality among the programs taken by different students, might have provided a basis for resistance to the fragmentation of the student body described by Mr. Levine.</p>
        <p>JAMES A. MCLENNAN  Bethlehem, Pa., June 11, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is professor emeritus of physics at Lehigh University.</p>
      </block>
